-- Crude Volatility Climbs as Futures Reach Highest Since Oct. 31
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-11-11T20:56:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-11/crude-volatility-climbs-as-futures-reach-highest-since-oct-31.html
Crude options volatility rose as the
underlying futures advanced to the highest level since Oct. 31.  Implied volatility for at-the-money January options, a
measure of expected futures swings and a key gauge of value, was
18.11 percent at 3:25 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile Exchange ,
up from 17.76 on Nov. 8. Puts protecting against a 10 percent
drop in prices increased to 23.65 percent compared with 23.01 in
the prior session.  West Texas Intermediate for January delivery climbed 52
cents to $95.47 a barrel on the Nymex. WTI crude for December
delivery rose 54 cents to $95.14.  Puts, or bets that prices would fall, accounted for 54
percent of electronic trading volume today. The most-active
options were December $96 calls, which dropped 1 cent to 39
cents a barrel with 2,188 lots trading as of 3:53 p.m. April $70
puts fell 1 cent to 16 cents on volume of 1,590 lots.  In the previous session, puts accounted for 51 percent of
the 84,136 lots traded. December $90 puts declined 23 cents to
42 cents a barrel on 3,184 contracts. April $65 puts fell 3
cents to 7 cents on volume of 2,860 lots.  Open interest Nov. 8 was highest for December $80 puts,
with 43,336 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 39,879
lots and December $85 puts with 36,874.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
